British Computer Society - Formal Aspects of Computing Science BCS - FACS : Call For Papers Formal Aspects of Human Computer Interaction Workshop , 5 th and 6 th September 1998 Sheffield Hallam University , Sheffield , UK . Human Computer Interaction ( HCI ) is a discipline in its relative infancy . However , its relevance is rapidly increasing with the growing number of users with a wide range of skill levels making greater demands upon interactive systems in a wide variety of contexts . Simply , it might be viewed as the offspring of the two disparate disciplines of psychology and computing . Others view it from a multi-disciplinary perspective drawing on a wide range of traditions ranging from science and engineering to art and craft . Some see this broad perspective as hampering its development whilst others see it as being its strength . One particular thread in HCI , thats been around for less than a decade and the focus of this series of workshops , is application of formality to HCI . What does formality have to offer in this debate about the foundations and nature of HCI ? What types of formality are relevant ? What are the benefits and limitations in applying formality to HCI ? Formality has a recognised place in computer science in general , and software engineering in particular , and the arguments have been frequently stated . Formality in computing rather like logic means reasoning involving the manipulation of mathematical symbols based on their form rather their meaning . In Art a formalism is a mode of expression in which form overrides content . In everyday parlance it has a broader characterisation , it means to act in accordance with rules and conventions . Are the arguments justifying the use formality in constructing software systems pertinent to HCI ? To what extent does the use of formality make explicit the concerns of human factors ? How do broader characterisations of formality assist in modelling and analysing interaction ? We strongly encourage submissions that directly address one or more of the above-mentioned concerns . Submissions which approach these concerns from the perspective of a specific topic are also invited . Relevant topics include , but are not limited to the following : Formalisation and analysis of requirements for interactive systems Application of formal techniques in interface specification , refinement and verification Representation and clarification of usability and temporal requirements in interaction The role of formality in the determining the foundations of HCI Applying formality to unify user , system and task models Specification and analysis of safety critical interfaces Models of multi-media interfaces and multi-modal interaction Empirical evaluations of formalisms and formal techniques Formal models of cognition Broader perspectives on and application of formality in HCI Refereed , accepted and presented papers will form the workshop proceedings to be published by Springer Verlag . Revised and developed versions of the best papers , a significant number of those presented at the workshop , were published in two special issues of journals : IEE Proceedings of Software Engineering ( Vol . 144 , No . 4 ) and Interacting with Computers ( Vol . 9 , No . 2 ) . Similarly , the development of quality workshop papers into journal publications is expected for 1998 . The workshop is scheduled to run immediatly after HCI 98 i . e . the weekend of 5 th and 6 th of September . It is organised under the auspices of The British Computer Society Formal Aspects of Computer Science ( BCS-FACS ) at Sheffield Hallam University by Prof . Jawed Siddiqi and Dr . Chris Roast . Last year a significant number of the key researchers in academia and industry in Formal Aspects of HCI were involved in the production of the technical programme of the workshop . These activities included peer group reviewing , submitting papers , chairing sessions and being a panellist . KEY DATES : Submission Deadline 29 th May Decisions on Papers 24 th July Return of Camera Ready Copy 14 th August PROGRAMME COMMITTEE : Jawed Siddiqi , Chris Roast , Alan Dix , Chris Johnson , Panos Markopoulos , Fabio Paterno , Michael Harrison , Andrew Hussey and Thomas Green .
